\p
\v 12 Then YahwehÂŠ338551 \add âgave\add* me \add another\add* messageÂŠ338549:
\v 13 âHumanity's child, when a \add âcountry\add* sins against me by \add âchoosing to worship other gods\add*, so that I \add âdecide to take action\add* against it, \add âthen\add* I'll breakÂŠ338569 the \add âcycle of foodÂŠ338573 production\add* and sendÂŠ338574 a famineÂŠ338577 out over it. I'll \add âpunish\add* both people and animalsÂŠ338581 from that land
\v 14 \add in such a way that\add* even if NoahÂŠ338588, Daniel, andÂŠ338583 YobÂŠ338592 \add (Job)\add* \add âlived in that place\add*, they could only rescueÂŠ338595 their own livesÂŠ338596 by being \add âblameless in my sight\add*. That's the masterÂŠ338598 Yahweh'sÂŠ338599 declaration.
\p
\v 15 If I send \add âvicious wild animals\add* through the \add âcountry\add* and make it barren so that it becomesÂŠ338608 a wasteland where no one can passÂŠ338605 through because of those animals,
\v 16 then even if those same threeÂŠ338615 menÂŠ338616 were inÂŠ338618 it, as IÂŠ338624 live, declares the masterÂŠ338623 YahwehÂŠ338623, they wouldn't be able to rescueÂŠ338631 even their own \add âchildren\add*âonly their own lives would be saved, butÂŠ338628 the land \add itself\add* would become a wasteland.
\p
\v 17 Or if I bringÂŠ338641 a sword against that \add âcountry\add* and say, âSword, go through the land and \add âeliminate both the\add* people and \add domestic\add* animalsÂŠ338653 from itâ,
\v 18 thenÂŠ338655 even if those threeÂŠ338655 menÂŠ338656 were inÂŠ338658 itÂŠ338658, as IÂŠ338664 live, declares the masterÂŠ338663 YahwehÂŠ338663, they wouldn't be able to rescueÂŠ338666 even their own sonsÂŠ338667 or daughtersÂŠ338668âonly their own lives would be saved.
\p
\v 19 Or if I sendÂŠ338676 a plague against that \add âcountry\add* and pour out my rageÂŠ338682 against it through bloodshedÂŠ338684, inÂŠ338684 order to \add âeliminate both the\add* people and the \add domestic\add* animalsÂŠ338688,
\v 20 as surely as I live, even if Noah, Daniel, and YobÂŠ338694 were in that country, they wouldn't be able to rescueÂŠ338708 even their sons and daughtersÂŠ338707. They'd save only themselves by being \add âblameless in myÂŠ338698 sight\add*. That's the masterÂŠ338700 Yahweh'sÂŠ338701 declaration.
\p
\v 21 TheÂŠ338719 masterÂŠ338718 YahwehÂŠ338718 saysÂŠ338717 this: âI'llÂŠ338732 certainly make things worse by sending my fourÂŠ338723 punishments againstÂŠ338733 YerushalemÂŠ338735 to \add âeliminate both the\add* people and the \add domestic\add* animals from it: famineÂŠ338728, swordÂŠ338727, wild animals, and plagueÂŠ338731.\x + \xo 14:21: \xt Rev 6:8.\x*
\v 22 \add âButÂŠ338741 listen!\add* \add Despite that,\add* a remnantÂŠ338745 will be left inÂŠ338744 \add @the city\add*âsurvivors who'll go out withÂŠ338744 sonsÂŠ338747 and daughtersÂŠ338748. \add âYes,\add* they'll go out to you, and you'll see their behaviour and actionsÂŠ338758 and \add âunderstand why they deserved\add* the punishment that I sent to YerushalemÂŠ338767, and aboutÂŠ338750 everything else that I'veÂŠ338764 sent against the \add âcountry\add*.
\v 23 The survivors will relieve you \add people\add* when you seeÂŠ338779 their behaviour andÂŠ338775 their actionsÂŠ338785, becauseÂŠ338777 you'll knowÂŠ338786 that all those things that I'veÂŠ338790 done against \add @Yerushalem\add*, I \add âdidn'tÂŠ338788 do them withoutÂŠ338789 good reason\add*. That's the masterÂŠ338799 Yahweh'sÂŠ338800 declaration.â
\c 15
\s1 The vine stem is useless as wood
\rem /s1 A Parable about a Vine; The people and their leaders condemned; Jerusalemâa Useless Vine; The Useless Vine; Jerusalem, A Useless Vine
\p
\v 1 Then YahwehÂŠ338806 \add âgave\add* me \add another\add* messageÂŠ338804:
\v 2 âHumanity's child, how is a vineÂŠ338818 better than any treeÂŠ338821 withÂŠ338825 branchesÂŠ338822 inÂŠ338825 a forestÂŠ338826?
\v 3 Do peopleÂŠ338835 takeÂŠ338835 wood from \add @a vine\add* to make anythingÂŠ338832? Would anyone \add âuse\add* \add @vine wood\add* \add even\add* to make something to hang a mug on?
\v 4 If it's \add âused as firewood\add*, and if the fire burns bothÂŠ338849 ends, and even the middleÂŠ338853, is it good \add wood, or indeed good\add* for anythingÂŠ338856?
\v 5 \add âOriginally,\add* \add @the vine wood\add* couldn't \add be used to\add* make anything, so surely, when the fire'sÂŠ338867 burnt it, it still can'tÂŠ338861 do anything useful.
\p
\v 6 Therefore the masterÂŠ338878 YahwehÂŠ338878 saysÂŠ338877 this: âUnlike the treesÂŠ338884 in the forestsÂŠ338885, I'veÂŠ338892 given the vineÂŠ338883 as fuel for fires. I'll act in the same way toward Yerushalem'sÂŠ338896 inhabitantsÂŠ338895,
\v 7 andÂŠ338898 I'llÂŠ338898 \add âstart to take action\add* against them. Even if they get out of the fire, the fire will still consumeÂŠ338906 them, so you \add people\add* will know that I am YahwehÂŠ338911, when I \add âtake action\add* against them.
\v 8 ThenÂŠ338918 I'llÂŠ338918 make the land into an abandoned wasteland becauseÂŠ338923 theyÂŠ338924 \add âchose to worship other gods\add*. That's the masterÂŠ338927 Yahweh'sÂŠ338928 declaration.â
\c 16
\s1 Unfaithful Yerushalem's vile practices
\rem /s1 Jerusalemâan Unfaithful Wife; Jerusalem the Unfaithful; An Allegory of Unfaithful Jerusalem; God's Faithless Bride
\p
\v 1 Then YahwehÂŠ338934 \add âgave\add* me \add another\add* messageÂŠ338932:
\v 2 âHumanity's child, inform YerushalemÂŠ338944 about \add âtheir detestable behaviour\add*,
\v 3 and declare that the masterÂŠ338953 YahwehÂŠ338953 saysÂŠ338952 this to YerushalemÂŠ338955: Your beginning and your birthÂŠ338957 took place in the land of Canaan, your fatherÂŠ338960 was an AmoriteÂŠ338961, and your motherÂŠ338962 was a HittiteÂŠ338963.\f + \fr 16:3 \ft A bunch of insults to the proud Israelis.\f*
\v 4 \add âWhenÂŠ338965 you were born\add*, your mother didn'tÂŠ338969 cut your cord, nor did she cleanÂŠ338977 you with waterÂŠ338973 or rub you down with salt, or wrap cloth around you.
\v 5 No \add âone cared enough\add* about you to do any of theseÂŠ338993 things for youâto be compassionate toward you. YourÂŠ339002 lifeÂŠ339002 \add âwas despised\add* \add and\add* you were thrownÂŠ338996 out into the open fieldÂŠ339000 onÂŠ339001 the \add very\add* dayÂŠ339003 that you were born.
\p
\v 6 ButÂŠ339007 I went past, andÂŠ339007 I saw you, \add Yerushalem,\add* writhing in your own blood, so I said to you \add as you lay there\add* in your blood, âLive!â\f + \fr 16:6 \ft The last part of the verse is repeated in the Hebrew.\f*
\v 7 I made you grow like a plantÂŠ339022 inÂŠ339028 the countrysideÂŠ339023. You grew up and became tall, and you became the \add âmost precious\add* jewelÂŠ339028. Your breastsÂŠ339030 became firm, and your hairÂŠ339032 grew thick, even though you'd been nakedÂŠ339035 and bare.
\p
\v 8 I wentÂŠ339052 past again and saw you. Wow, the time of love came for you, so I spreadÂŠ339045 my robe out over you and coveredÂŠ339048 yourÂŠ339042 nakednessÂŠ339049. ThenÂŠ339038 I \add âmade a promise\add* to you and brought you into a contract and you becameÂŠ339058 mine. That's the masterÂŠ339056 Yahweh'sÂŠ339057 declaration.
\p
\v 9 I washedÂŠ339063 you, \add Yerushalem,\add* withÂŠ339062 waterÂŠ339062, and rinsed your bloodÂŠ339064 off you, and I \add âput lotion onÂŠ339062 your skin\add*.
\v 10 ThenÂŠ339069 I dressed you in embroidered clothesÂŠ339069 andÂŠ339069 put leatherÂŠ339072 sandalsÂŠ339071 onÂŠ339074 your feet. I wrappedÂŠ339073 you in fine linenÂŠ339074, thenÂŠ339069 coveredÂŠ339075 you withÂŠ339074 silk.
\v 11 Next I adornedÂŠ339078 youÂŠ339078 with jewellery, and I put braceletsÂŠ339081 on your handsÂŠ339084 and a chainÂŠ339085 around your neck.
\v 12 I put a ring in your noseÂŠ339094 and earringsÂŠ339095 in your earsÂŠ339098, and a beautifulÂŠ339100 crownÂŠ339099 onÂŠ339101 your headÂŠ339101.
\v 13 SoÂŠ339103 you were adornedÂŠ339103 withÂŠ339117 goldÂŠ339104 and silverÂŠ339105, and you were dressed inÂŠ339117 fine linenÂŠ339107, silk, and embroideredÂŠ339110 clothesÂŠ339106. You ateÂŠ339114 \add good food made from\add* fine flourÂŠ339111, honeyÂŠ339112, and oilÂŠ339113, and you were very beautifulÂŠ339116, and you became a queenÂŠ339120.
\v 14 Your \add âreputationÂŠ339124\add*, \add Yerushalem,\add* \add âspread\add* amongÂŠ339125 the nationsÂŠ339125 because of your beautyÂŠ339126, because it was perfectÂŠ339129 inÂŠ339125 the majesty I'd given you. That's the masterÂŠ339137 Yahweh'sÂŠ339138 declaration.
\p
\v 15 ButÂŠ339140 \add Yerushalem,\add* you trustedÂŠ339140 inÂŠ339141 your own beauty, and you actedÂŠ339142 like a prostitute because of your reputationÂŠ339145. You \add âflirted withÂŠ339141 everyoneÂŠ339152 going past, and prostituted yourself\add*, so that your beauty became theirs.
\v 16 ThenÂŠ339159 you tookÂŠ339159 yourÂŠ339160 clothesÂŠ339160 and made \add âhilltop shrines\add* for yourself with them, decorated in various colours, and there you actedÂŠ339166 like a prostituteÂŠ339166. This shouldn'tÂŠ339168 have happened, nor should such a thing exist.
\v 17 You tookÂŠ339173 the fine goldÂŠ339176 and silverÂŠ339177 jewellery thatÂŠ339178 I gaveÂŠ339179 you, and you made maleÂŠ339185 sculptures for yourselves, and you \add âbehaved withÂŠ339188 them like a prostituteÂŠ339186 would\add*.
\v 18 You tookÂŠ339190 yourÂŠ339194 embroideredÂŠ339194 garments and coveredÂŠ339195 \add @those idols\add*, and youÂŠ339198 \add âoffered\add* my oils and perfumes to them.
\v 19 The \add high-quality\add* breadÂŠ339202 thatÂŠ339203 I gaveÂŠ339205 you (made with fine flourÂŠ339207, oilÂŠ339208, and honeyÂŠ339209), you placed \add âin front of\add* them to be a fragrant aromaÂŠ339213, \add âand indeed itÂŠ339211 was\add*. That's the masterÂŠ339217 Yahweh'sÂŠ339218 declaration.
\p
\v 20 ThenÂŠ339220 you tookÂŠ339220 your sonsÂŠ339223 and daughtersÂŠ339226 that you bore for me, and you sacrificedÂŠ339230 them to \add @those idols\add* to be devouredÂŠ339232 as food. Are your acts of prostitutionÂŠ339234 a smallÂŠ339233 matter?
\v 21 You slaughteredÂŠ339237 my childrenÂŠ339240 for the idols andÂŠ339241 made them passÂŠ339242 throughÂŠ339242 the fire.
\v 22 In all your \add âevil goings onÂŠ339258\add* and your acts of prostitutionÂŠ339250, you \add ânever thought back to\add* the daysÂŠ339256 \add âwhen you were young\add*, when you were nakedÂŠ339259 and bare as you thrashed aboutÂŠ339261 inÂŠ339258 your \add own\add* bloodÂŠ339262.
\rem /s1 Jerusalem's Life as a Prostitute
\v 23 After all yourÂŠ339269 wickednessÂŠ339269, \add âyou won't end well\add*. That's the masterÂŠ339274 Yahweh'sÂŠ339275 declaration.
\s1 The anger of God on Yerushalem
\p
\v 24 You made yourself a moundÂŠ339280 andÂŠ339282 builtÂŠ339277 a raised shrine in every public square.
\v 25 You builtÂŠ339296 your raised platform at the top of everyÂŠ339292 street and made your beautyÂŠ339301 a disgrace, and you spreadÂŠ339302 your legs for anyoneÂŠ339308 who passedÂŠ339308 by, and you multiplied your acts of prostitutionÂŠ339298.
\v 26 You've actedÂŠ339315 like a prostitute with your lusty neighboursÂŠ339321 the Egyptians, andÂŠ339315 you committed many more acts of prostitution, provokingÂŠ339328 me to angerÂŠ339328.
\p
\v 27 Listen, I'll hit you withÂŠ339337 my hand andÂŠ339330 cut off your food \add supply\add*. I'll hand your life over to your enemiesÂŠ339338, the daughtersÂŠ339339 of the PhilistinesÂŠ339340, who were ashamedÂŠ339341 of your obscene behaviour.
\p
\v 28 You've acted like a prostitute with the Assyrians becauseÂŠ339350 you couldn't be satisfied. You acted like a prostitute andÂŠ339345 still you weren't satisfied.
\v 29 \add âSoÂŠ339357\add* you performed many more acts of prostitutionÂŠ339360 inÂŠ339368 \add Babylonia\add* (the \add âcountry\add* of the ChaldeanÂŠ339365 merchantsÂŠ339364), andÂŠ339357 even that didn'tÂŠ339369 satisfyÂŠ339370 you.
\v 30 Your heartÂŠ339374 is so sick that you would do things like thatâthings that only a shameless prostituteÂŠ339387 would do. That's the masterÂŠ339376 Yahweh'sÂŠ339377 declaration.
\p
\v 31 You made your moundsÂŠ339391 at the top of every street and builtÂŠ339390 your tall shrines in every public square, \add âyet\add* you weren't like a prostituteÂŠ339406, \add âin the sense that\add* you scoffed at taking payment.
\v 32 You adulterousÂŠ339411 womanÂŠ339410, you \add âprefer\add* strangersÂŠ339417 \add âover\add* your husbandÂŠ339413.
\v 33 \add It's normal for\add* \add âclients to pay\add* the prostitute, butÂŠ339425 you \add do the opposite\add*: you giveÂŠ339422 your wages to all your loversÂŠ339432 and bribeÂŠ339433 them to comeÂŠ339435 to you from all aroundÂŠ339437 for your acts of prostitution.
\v 34 \add âYes,\add* there's a difference between you andÂŠ339440 other womenÂŠ339446. No one offers paymentÂŠ339453 for you to act as a prostituteÂŠ339450. You're the very oppositeÂŠ339459âyou \add âpaid\add* them \add âbutÂŠ339440\add* nothing was givenÂŠ339455 to you.
\s1 The punishment of God of Yerushalem
\rem /s1 Judgment on Jerusalem's Prostitution; God's Judgment on Jerusalem
\p
\v 35 Therefore, \add Yerushalem\add*, you prostituteÂŠ339462, listenÂŠ339463 to Yahweh'sÂŠ339466 messageÂŠ339464.
\v 36 The masterÂŠ339472 YahwehÂŠ339472 saysÂŠ339471 this: âBecause you've pouredÂŠ339475 out your lust and uncoveredÂŠ339477 your nakednessÂŠ339478 through your acts of prostitutionÂŠ339479 with your loversÂŠ339482 and with all your detestableÂŠ339487 idolsÂŠ339486, and becauseÂŠ339474 you gaveÂŠ339491 them your children'sÂŠ339489 bloodÂŠ339488,
\v 37 then listen: I'll gather all your loversÂŠ339501 that you've met, \add âincludingÂŠ339505 the ones\add* you lovedÂŠ339509 and the ones you hatedÂŠ339514âI'll gather them againstÂŠ339517 you on every side. I'll uncoverÂŠ339519 your nakedness for them so they see all your nakedness.
\v 38 ThenÂŠ339529 I'll punish you for your adulteryÂŠ339531 and the shedding of blood, and I'll bringÂŠ339534 on you the bloodshed of my anger and passion.
\v 39 I'llÂŠ339539 \add âallow them to conquer you\add* so they'll \add âtear apart\add* your moundsÂŠ339543 and breakÂŠ339544 down your tallÂŠ339545 shrinesÂŠ339545, and they'll stripÂŠ339546 your clothesÂŠ339548 off you and takeÂŠ339549 all your jewelleryâleaving you nakedÂŠ339553 and bare.
\p
\v 40 ThenÂŠ339556 they'll bringÂŠ339556 a crowd up againstÂŠ339557 you and \add âthrow heavy stonesÂŠ339561 atÂŠ339561 you\add*, and they'll cut you apart withÂŠ339561 theirÂŠ339563 swordsÂŠ339563.
\v 41 They'll burnÂŠ339565 down your housesÂŠ339566 and \add âpunish you in several ways\add* in the sightÂŠ339572 of many womenÂŠ339573, because I'llÂŠ339575 put a stop to your prostitutionÂŠ339576, and you'll no longer pay your lovers.
\v 42 ThenÂŠ339585 I'll calm my rageÂŠ339586 againstÂŠ339594 you. My angerÂŠ339586 will leave you, because I'll be satisfiedÂŠ339585 andÂŠ339585 won'tÂŠ339592 be angryÂŠ339593 \add at you\add* any longer.
\p
\v 43 BecauseÂŠ339596 you didn'tÂŠ339598 call to mind your younger daysÂŠ339604, and made me shake withÂŠ339618 anger because of all those things, thereforeÂŠ339615, listen: I myself will bring the punishment for what you've done down onto your own headÂŠ339618. That's the masterÂŠ339621 Yahweh'sÂŠ339622 declaration.
\s1 Ke what the mother like just the child woman
\p Haven't you added prostitution to all your other detestable practices?
\rem /s1 Like Mother, Like Daughter
\v 44 Listen, everyoneÂŠ339635 who speaksÂŠ339639 proverbsÂŠ339637 aboutÂŠ339638 youÂŠ339638 will sayÂŠ339640, âLike motherÂŠ339641, like daughterÂŠ339642.â
\v 45 You are the daughterÂŠ339644 of your mother, who detested her husband and her children, and you are the sister of your sisters, who detested their husbands and their children. YourÂŠ339646 mother was a HittiteÂŠ339659, and your fatherÂŠ339660 was an AmoriteÂŠ339661.
\p
\v 46 YourÂŠ339671 olderÂŠ339664 sister was ShomronÂŠ339665 \add (SamariaÂŠ339665)\add*, and her daughters were the ones living in the northÂŠ339671, while yourÂŠ339671 youngerÂŠ339673 sister was the one living southÂŠ339676 of you, that is, SodomÂŠ339677 and her daughters.
\v 47 \add âNot only did you follow\add* their customs and copy their behaviourÂŠ339688 and practices, butÂŠ339680 inÂŠ339681 \add âeverything you did\add*, you've been \em worse\em* than they were.
\p
\v 48 This is the masterÂŠ339698 Yahweh'sÂŠ339699 declaration: As I live, your sisterÂŠ339704 SodomÂŠ339703 and her daughters didn't do as much evil as you and your daughters have done.
\v 49 Listen, yourÂŠ339718 sisterÂŠ339718 Sodom'sÂŠ339717 sin was that sheÂŠ339733 was arrogant in herÂŠ339727 leisure, careless and unconcerned about anything. She didn'tÂŠ339732 \add âassist\add* the poor and needyÂŠ339731 people.
\v 50 She was arrogant andÂŠ339735 performed disgusting actions \add âin front of\add* me, so I took them away, just as you've seen.
\p
\v 51 As for ShomronÂŠ339745, they didn'tÂŠ339748 commit even half of your sinsÂŠ339747. No, you've doneÂŠ339764 many more disgusting things than they did, and you've shown thatÂŠ339763 your sistersÂŠ339758 were better than you, because of all the disgusting things you do.
\v 52 Also how you display your own shameâyou'veÂŠ339774 shown thatÂŠ339777 your sisters were better than you by the sinsÂŠ339776 you committed inÂŠ339776 all those disgusting ways. Your sisters now seem better than you.
\rem /s1 Sodom and Samaria Will Be Restored
\p
\v 53 From theirÂŠ339795 captivity, I'llÂŠ339792 restoreÂŠ339792 the fortunes of SodomÂŠ339800 and her daughters, and of ShomronÂŠ339806 and her daughters, and your fortunes \add âwill be similar\add*,\f + \fr 16:53 \ft i.e., to go into captivity, but then after a time, to be restored.\f*
\v 54 so that you'll display yourÂŠ339815 shame. You'll be humiliated because of everything you'veÂŠ339820 doneÂŠ339820, and inÂŠ339821 that way you'll be a consolationÂŠ339821 to \add @Sodom and Shomron\add*.
\v 55 Your sisterÂŠ339824 SodomÂŠ339825 and her daughters will be restored to their former condition, and ShomronÂŠ339829 and her daughters will be restored \add âsimilarly\add*. ThenÂŠ339824 you and your daughters will be restored to your former condition.
\v 56 \add âYou never even mentionedÂŠ339842 your sisterÂŠ339841 SodomÂŠ339840 inÂŠ339843 the period when you were proud\add*,
\v 57 beforeÂŠ339847 your wickednessÂŠ339849 was revealed. ButÂŠ339856 now you're an object of scorn to the daughters of AramÂŠ339855 \add (SyriaÂŠ339855)\add* and to all the daughters of the PhilistinesÂŠ339860 around herÂŠ339858. People all around despiseÂŠ339861 you.
\v 58 You'll display your shame and your disgusting actions. That's Yahweh'sÂŠ339874 declaration.
\s1 The agreement without ending
\rem /s1 An Everlasting Covenant; A Covenant That Lasts Forever
\p
\v 59 TheÂŠ339881 masterÂŠ339880 YahwehÂŠ339880 saysÂŠ339879 this: âI'llÂŠ339882 deal with you as you deserveâyou who've despisedÂŠ339889 your oath by breakingÂŠ339891 \add &our\add* agreementÂŠ339892.
\v 60 ButÂŠ339894 I myself will call to mind my agreement with you that was made \add âwhen you were younger\add*, andÂŠ339894 I'llÂŠ339894 establishÂŠ339902 a never-ending agreement with you.
\v 61 ThenÂŠ339907 you'll call to mind your behaviour and be ashamedÂŠ339911 when you \add âadopt\add* your olderÂŠ339916 and youngerÂŠ339920 sistersÂŠ339915. I'llÂŠ339922 giveÂŠ339922 them to you as daughtersÂŠ339925, butÂŠ339907 not because of your agreementÂŠ339927.
\v 62 I myself will establishÂŠ339929 my agreementÂŠ339933 with you, andÂŠ339935 you'll knowÂŠ339935 that I am YahwehÂŠ339939,
\v 63 so that you'll call everything to mind and be ashamedÂŠ339943. Then you'll no longer open your mouthÂŠ339950 to speak, because of your shame, when I've forgivenÂŠ339953 you for everything you'veÂŠ339959 doneÂŠ339959. That's the masterÂŠ339961 Yahweh'sÂŠ339962 declaration.â â
\c 17
\s1 The two eagles and the vine
\rem /s1 A Story of Two Eagles; The Two Eagles and the Vine; Two Eagles and a Vine; The Parable of the Eagles and the Vine
\p
\v 1 Then YahwehÂŠ339968 \add âgave\add* me \add another\add* messageÂŠ339966:
\v 2 âHumanity'sÂŠ339982 child, present a riddle andÂŠ339977 tellÂŠ339977 a parableÂŠ339978 to the \add âIsraeliÂŠ339981 people\add*.
\v 3 Tell \add >them\add*, âThe masterÂŠ339989 YahwehÂŠ339989 saysÂŠ339987 this: âA large eagleÂŠ339991, with large wingsÂŠ339994 full of multi-coloured feathersÂŠ339996, and longÂŠ339995 pinions, wentÂŠ340003 to LebanonÂŠ340006 and grabbed hold of the top of a cedarÂŠ340011 tree.
\v 4 He broke off the top shootÂŠ340015 of \add @the tree\add* and took it to Canaan \add where he\add* placedÂŠ340024 it inÂŠ340022 a cityÂŠ340022 \add full\add* of merchantsÂŠ340021.
\v 5 He \add âalso\add* tookÂŠ340026 some of the land's seed andÂŠ340026 planted it inÂŠ340030 fertile soil, \add âbeside a large body of waterÂŠ340036 where\add* a willowÂŠ340038 \add might grow\add*.
\v 6 ThenÂŠ340041 \add @the seed\add* sproutedÂŠ340041 and became a spreading vine low to the ground. Its branches turnedÂŠ340047 toward him, and its rootsÂŠ340050 grew \add âdown below\add*, so it became a vine and producedÂŠ340055 branches and sent out shootsÂŠ340056.
\p
\v 7 \add âButÂŠ340060\add* there was another large eagle with large wingsÂŠ340066 and many feathers. Oh wow, that vineÂŠ340071 turned its rootsÂŠ340074 toward this eagle, and it spread out its branchesÂŠ340076 toward the eagle from the place it had been plantedÂŠ340083 so it might get wateredÂŠ340080.
\v 8 It had been plantedÂŠ340094 in goodÂŠ340088 soil beside a large body of waterÂŠ340091 so it would grow branchesÂŠ340096 and produceÂŠ340098 fruitÂŠ340098, to become a magnificent vineÂŠ340100.â
\p
\v 9 \add âAsk\add* \add the people\add*: âThe masterÂŠ340107 YahwehÂŠ340107 wants to know if it'll prosperÂŠ340109. Won't it be uprooted and strippedÂŠ340119 of its fruitÂŠ340117 so that it withersÂŠ340120, and all its freshÂŠ340123 growthÂŠ340124 will dry out? \add âYou wouldn't have to be very strong or get lots of people to help\add* to pull it out by its roots.
\v 10 SoÂŠ340137 listen. After it had been plantedÂŠ340138, would it thriveÂŠ340139? Wouldn't it wither up when the easternÂŠ340144 windÂŠ340143 touchesÂŠ340141 it? \add Yes,\add* it would wither right up inÂŠ340142 the garden plot whereÂŠ340150 it sprouted.â â
\s1 The vine part of the parable explained
\rem /s1 The Riddle Explained; The Parable Is Explained
\p
\v 11 Then YahwehÂŠ340157 \add âgave\add* me \add another\add* messageÂŠ340155:
\v 12 â\add âAsk\add* those rebelliousÂŠ340165 \add âpeople\add*, âDon'tÂŠ340166 you know what those things mean? Listen, the king of Babylon came to YerushalemÂŠ340178 and captured its king and its princesÂŠ340185 and took them with him to Babylon.\x + \xo 17:12-15: \xt 2Ki 24:15-20; 2Ch 36:10.\x*
\v 13 Then he took \add a member\add* of the royalÂŠ340193 familyÂŠ340192, made an agreementÂŠ340196 withÂŠ340199 himâ\add âforcing him to make various commitments\add*. Then he took away the \add âcountry's\add* \add former\add* powerful people,
\v 14 so the kingdomÂŠ340207 would remain \add âsubjected and not be able to become powerful again\add*. \add However,\add* by keeping the agreementÂŠ340214, the \add âcountry\add* would \add at least\add* survive.
\v 15 ButÂŠ340217 the king of Yerushalem rebelledÂŠ340217 against him by sendingÂŠ340220 his ambassadorsÂŠ340221 to EgyptÂŠ340222 \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* to acquire horsesÂŠ340226 andÂŠ340217 an army. Will he succeedÂŠ340230? Will the one doing theseÂŠ340233 things escape? If he breaksÂŠ340234 the agreementÂŠ340235, will he \add âsurvive\add*?
\v 16 This is the masterÂŠ340242 Yahweh'sÂŠ340243 declaration: As I live, he'll definitely die in the land of the king who made him king, the king whose promises he despisedÂŠ340252, and whose agreementÂŠ340260 he brokeÂŠ340257. He'll die in the middle of BabylonÂŠ340264.
\v 17 \add Egypt's\add* Far-oh \add (PharaohÂŠ340274)\add* withÂŠ340268 his mighty army and hugeÂŠ340269 hordeÂŠ340270 won'tÂŠ340267 help himÂŠ340273 inÂŠ340268 battleÂŠ340275, when ramps are constructed and siegeÂŠ340279 walls are builtÂŠ340278 up to cut off many livesÂŠ340281,
\v 18 because the king despisedÂŠ340284 his promise by breakingÂŠ340286 the agreementÂŠ340287. Wow, he reached out to make a promise, andÂŠ340284 yet \add afterwards\add* he didÂŠ340294 all those things. He won'tÂŠ340295 escapeÂŠ340296.
\v 19 Therefore the masterÂŠ340303 YahwehÂŠ340303 saysÂŠ340302 this: âAs I live, wasn't it my promise that he despisedÂŠ340313 and my agreementÂŠ340314 that he brokeÂŠ340316? \add âTherefore\add* I'llÂŠ340317 \add âcause him to be punished for what he did\add*.
\v 20 I'll spreadÂŠ340320 my netÂŠ340322 out over him, and he'll be caughtÂŠ340323 inÂŠ340324 my trap, and I'll take him to BabylonÂŠ340326 and handle his judgementÂŠ340327 thereÂŠ340329 for the treason he committed when he betrayed me.
\v 21 All of his refugees in his armies will be killed by the swordÂŠ340344, andÂŠ340336 the ones who remain will be scatteredÂŠ340350 in every direction. ThenÂŠ340336 you \add people\add* will knowÂŠ340351 that I am YahwehÂŠ340354, becauseÂŠ340352 I'veÂŠ340355 declared that that will happen.â
\s1 The tree-tip part of the parable explained
\rem /s1 God's Promise of Hope; Israel Exalted at Last
\p
\v 22 The masterÂŠ340360 YahwehÂŠ340360 saysÂŠ340359 this, âSo I myself will takeÂŠ340362 away the highest part of the cedarÂŠ340365 tree, and I'll plant it away from itsÂŠ340369 tenderÂŠ340370 branches. I'll break it off, and I myself will plant it on a very highÂŠ340377 mountainÂŠ340375.
\v 23 I'llÂŠ340383 plantÂŠ340383 it onÂŠ340398 Yisrael's highest mountainÂŠ340380 so it'll grow branches and produceÂŠ340384 fruitÂŠ340387, and it'll become a majesticÂŠ340390 cedarÂŠ340389 so that every winged bird will live underÂŠ340392 it. They'll nest inÂŠ340398 the shadeÂŠ340398 of its branches,
\v 24 thenÂŠ340402 all the trees in the countrysideÂŠ340406 will know that I am Yahweh. I bringÂŠ340410 down the high trees and I raiseÂŠ340414 up the low trees. I wither the watered tree and I cause the wilted tree to bloom. I am Yahweh. I'veÂŠ340425 declared that that will happen, and I will do it.â â
\c 18
\s1 Individual responsibility
\rem /s1 The Justice of a Righteous God; Individual Responsibility; The Soul Who Sins Will Die; Individual Retribution
\p
\v 1 Then YahwehÂŠ340432 \add âgave\add* me \add another\add* messageÂŠ340430:
\v 2 âWhat do you mean, you \add people\add* who use this proverb about YisraelÂŠ340448? You sayÂŠ340449, âFathers eatÂŠ340451 sour grapesÂŠ340452, \add âbutÂŠ340453 it's\add* the children'sÂŠ340454 teethÂŠ340453 that are \add âset on edge\add*â.
\p
\v 3 This is the masterÂŠ340461 Yahweh'sÂŠ340462 declaration: as I live, there'll \add âcertainly no longer be any occasion for youÂŠ340466 to use\add* this proverb inÂŠ340471 YisraelÂŠ340471.
\v 4 Listen, every life belongs to me: the father'sÂŠ340480 life as well as the son'sâthey belong to me. The \add âone who disobeys\add* is the one who'll die.
\s2 The godly man
\p
\v 5 If there's a \add âgodlyÂŠ340496\add* \add >man\add* who does what's fair and rightÂŠ340496,
\v 6 who doesn't eat at the \add âhilltop\add* \add shrines\add*, who doesn't \add ârequest help\add* from Yisrael'sÂŠ340513 idolsÂŠ340511, who doesn't \add âmess with\add* someone else's wifeÂŠ340516 or a menstruatingÂŠ340523 womanÂŠ340522,
\v 7 who doesn't oppressÂŠ340529 anyoneÂŠ340527, who gives back to debtors what they put up as security for loans, who doesn't \add âsteal\add* \add butÂŠ340527 rather\add* gives his food to the hungryÂŠ340537 andÂŠ340539 \add âgives clothesÂŠ340542 to those without them\add*,
\v 8 who doesn't charge too much interestÂŠ340544 if he lends \add >money\add*, and doesn't take too much profit for what he sells, who promotes true justiceÂŠ340554 \add âwithin the community\add*,
\v 9 who \add âfollows\add* my instructionsÂŠ340561 and \add âfaithfullyÂŠ340566 obeys\add* my regulationsÂŠ340561, that man will be \add âacquitted\add* \add and\add* will definitely live. That's the masterÂŠ340572 Yahweh'sÂŠ340573 declaration.\x + \xo 18:9: \xt Lev 18:5.\x*
\s3 The wayward son of the godly man
\p
\v 10 \add âButÂŠ340575\add* suppose \add @that godly man\add* has a violentÂŠ340578 son who kills andÂŠ340581 sadly \add âgoes against all those things above\add*,
\v 11 not \add âfollowing\add* the example of his \add âgodly\add* father, butÂŠ340586 \add rather\add* who's eatenÂŠ340599 at the \add âhilltop\add* \add shrines\add* andÂŠ340600 \add âslept with someone else's\add* wifeÂŠ340602,
\v 12 who oppressesÂŠ340608 the poor and needyÂŠ340607, who steals and robs, who doesn't returnÂŠ340613 \add something given as\add* a pledgeÂŠ340611, who \add ârequests help from\add* idolsÂŠ340616 and does \add âdisgusting things\add*,
\v 13 who lends out money at too high interestÂŠ340622, and who makes too much profit on what he sells. Should that man live? He certainlyÂŠ340635 won'tÂŠ340627! He'll definitely dieÂŠ340635, and his bloodÂŠ340637 will be on \add âhis own head\add*.
\s3 The peace/prosperity of child righteous/honest/sensible
\p
\v 14 ButÂŠ340641 listen, suppose he has a son, and his son sees all the sinsÂŠ340649 thatÂŠ340651 his father'sÂŠ340650 committed, and though he sees them, he doesn't do those things.
\v 15 He hasn't eatenÂŠ340662 at the \add âhilltop\add* \add shrines\add*, and hasn't \add ârequested help from the IsraeliÂŠ340670 people's idolsÂŠ340668\add*, and hasn't \add âslept with someone else's\add* wifeÂŠ340673,
\v 16 he doesn't oppressÂŠ340680 anyoneÂŠ340678, or \add âkeep things givenÂŠ340689 as\add* a pledge, or \add âaccept\add* stolen things, butÂŠ340678 instead gives his food to the hungryÂŠ340688 andÂŠ340678 \add âgives clothesÂŠ340693 to those without them\add*,
\v 17 he's turnedÂŠ340696 his back onÂŠ340704 \add âcrime\add*, and doesn't charge high interestÂŠ340698, he \add âfollows\add* my instructionsÂŠ340704 and \add âobeys\add* my regulationsÂŠ340704âhe won'tÂŠ340700 dieÂŠ340708 for his father'sÂŠ340710 \add âevil actions\add*, butÂŠ340699 he'll certainlyÂŠ340711 live.
\v 18 His fatherÂŠ340714, since he oppressed others by extortionÂŠ340717 and robbedÂŠ340719 \add âpeople\add*, and did \add âevil things\add* among his peopleâlisten, he'll dieÂŠ340731 inÂŠ340732 his sin.
\p
\v 19 \add âButÂŠ340734 you people ask\add*, âWhy doesn't the son \add also\add* have to \add pay the cost for his family's crimes\add*?â \add Well\add* it's because the son \add âpromotes\add* justiceÂŠ340743 and godliness and \add âfollows\add* all my instructionsÂŠ340749. He'll definitely live.
\v 20 The one who sins is the one who'll die. The children won't \add have to\add* \add âbe responsible for\add* their parents' sin, and the parents won't \add âbe responsible for\add* their children's sinsâthe righteousness of those who act rightly will be on themselves, and the wickedness of the wicked will be on themselves.\x + \xo 18:20: \xt Deu 24:16.\x*
\s2 The person repent of sins he/his
\p
\v 21 \add âButÂŠ340783\add* if the wickedÂŠ340783 \add >person\add* turns away from all \add âtheir disobedience\add*, and \add âfollows\add* all my instructionsÂŠ340797 and \add âdoes what's rightÂŠ340800 and fair\add*, then \add @that person\add* will certainlyÂŠ340801 live and not dieÂŠ340804.
\v 22 All \add âtheir acts of disobedience\add* won'tÂŠ340811 be called to mind against them. They'll liveÂŠ340818 by the \add ârightÂŠ340814 things theyÂŠ340812 do\add*.
\v 23 That's the masterÂŠ340825 Yahweh'sÂŠ340826 declaration.
\p Do I \add âcelebrate happily\add* about the deathÂŠ340822 of wickedÂŠ340823 \add people\add*, andÂŠ340830 not about them turningÂŠ340828 away from their \add evil\add* behaviourÂŠ340829 so that they can liveÂŠ340830?
\v 24 \add âButÂŠ340833\add* if a righteous person turnsÂŠ340833 away from their righteousness, and \add âdisobeys\add* and \add âdoes disgusting things like\add* the wickedÂŠ340843 people do, then will they liveÂŠ340845? All the \add âgood things\add* that had been done won'tÂŠ340853 be called to mind when they betray me in their treason, so they'll dieÂŠ340864 in the sins that they committedÂŠ340836.
\p
\v 25 \add âButÂŠ340866 you people complain\add* that the master'sÂŠ340870 way isn'tÂŠ340867 correct. PleaseÂŠ340875 listenÂŠ340871, \add you\add* \add âIsraeliÂŠ340874 people\add*: is it my ways that aren'tÂŠ340867 correct, or is it \em your\em* ways?
\v 26 When the righteous person turnsÂŠ340884 away from their righteousness, and commits injustice and dies because of it, then \add *that person\add* will die inÂŠ340892 the injustice that they've done.
\v 27 \add âButÂŠ340899\add* when a wicked person turnsÂŠ340899 away from the wicked things they've doneÂŠ340903 and \add âdoes what's fair and what's rightÂŠ340906\add*, then \add *that person\add* will preserveÂŠ340911 their lifeÂŠ340910â
\v 28 they've \add âbecome aware of all their disobedient behaviours\add* andÂŠ340913 turnedÂŠ340914 away from them. \add @That person\add* certainlyÂŠ340921 won'tÂŠ340923 dieÂŠ340924, \add âbutÂŠ340913\add* will live.
\v 29 \add âButÂŠ340926 the IsraeliÂŠ340928 people insist\add*, âThe master'sÂŠ340932 way isn'tÂŠ340929 fair!â How is my way not fair, \add âyou IsraeliÂŠ340928 people\add*? It's \em your\em* ways that aren'tÂŠ340929 fair.
\v 30 Therefore I'llÂŠ340947 judgeÂŠ340947 each person among you accordingÂŠ340946 to their waysÂŠ340946, \add âyou IsraeliÂŠ340949 people\add*. That's the masterÂŠ340952 Yahweh'sÂŠ340953 declaration.
\p \add âChange your direction\add* and turn away from all your \add âdisobedient behaviours\add* so that they won'tÂŠ340959 be stumblingÂŠ340963 blocksÂŠ340963 of evilÂŠ340964 for you.
\v 31 ThrowÂŠ340966 off all the \add âdisobedient things you people have done\add*. \add âWork towards\add* a new heartÂŠ340978 and a new spiritÂŠ340980 for yourselves. Why should you dieÂŠ340983, \add âyou IsraeliÂŠ340985 people\add*?
\v 32 I takeÂŠ340989 no pleasureÂŠ340989 inÂŠ340990 the deathÂŠ340990 of someone who diesÂŠ340991. That's the masterÂŠ340993 Yahweh'sÂŠ340994 declaration, \add so\add* \add âturnÂŠ340995 away from your evil behaviour\add* and liveÂŠ340996.
\c 19
