\c 31
\s1 Egypt gets compared to fallen Assyria
\rem /s1 Egypt Is Compared to a Cedar Tree; A Cedar in Lebanon; Egypt Compared to Fallen Assyria; The Lofty Cedar
\p
\v 1 \add âAt the end of June\add* inÂŠ346874 the eleventh yearÂŠ346876 \add since King Yoyakin (Jehoiachin) had been taken captive\add*,\f + \fr 31:1 \ft 587 B.C.\f* YahwehÂŠ346883 \add âgave me\add* a messageÂŠ346881:
\v 2 âHumanity's child, \add âask\add* the Egyptian kingÂŠ346894 Far-oh \add (PharaohÂŠ346893)\add* and his multitudesÂŠ346899 around him, â\add âWho else is as powerful as youÂŠ346903 and yourÂŠ346904 peopleÂŠ346899\add*?
\v 3 Listen, AssyriaÂŠ346907 was \add like\add* a cedarÂŠ346908 inÂŠ346909 LebanonÂŠ346909 withÂŠ346909 beautifulÂŠ346910 branches, giving shadeÂŠ346913 to the forestÂŠ346912âextremely tall, and the branches formed its treetopÂŠ346919.
\v 4 \add âA deep water supply\add* made it grow tall. Rivers flowed all aroundÂŠ346929 its area, because their channelsÂŠ346933 stretched out to all the treesÂŠ346938 in the countrysideÂŠ346939.
\v 5 It \add âgrew taller\add* than any of the other treesÂŠ346947 in the countrysideÂŠ346948, and its branchesÂŠ346952 grew longÂŠ346951 and \add âthick\add* becauseÂŠ346954 of \add âhaving plenty of\add* waterÂŠ346954 in its shootsÂŠ346956.
\v 6 Every \add âkind of\add* bird nested in its branchesÂŠ346965, while every living thing in the countrysideÂŠ346969 gaveÂŠ346966 birthÂŠ346966 to its young under the foliage of that tree. All the powerful nationsÂŠ346973 lived under its shadeÂŠ346970.
\v 7 It was beautifulÂŠ346976 inÂŠ346977 its greatnessÂŠ346977 andÂŠ346976 due to the lengthÂŠ346978 of its branchesÂŠ346979, becauseÂŠ346980 its rootsÂŠ346983 \add âhad access to\add* many waterÂŠ346986 \add sources\add*.
\v 8 CedarÂŠ346989 trees in God's garden couldn't equal it. None of the cypress trees matched its branches, nor could its branches be equalled by the planeÂŠ347002 tree. There was no other tree in God's garden that could compare to its beautyÂŠ347017.\x + \xo 31:8: \xt Gen 2:9.\x*
\v 9 I made it beautiful withÂŠ347021 its many branchesÂŠ347022, and all the treesÂŠ347026 in God's gardenÂŠ347030 in EdenÂŠ347028 enviedÂŠ347023 it.
\p
\v 10 Therefore the masterÂŠ347037 YahwehÂŠ347037 saysÂŠ347036 this: Because it was so tall, and it set its treetopÂŠ347044 betweenÂŠ347047 its branchesÂŠ347048, and \add âĄbecause\add* it \add âgrew proudÂŠ347049\add* of its heightÂŠ347051,
\v 11 I \add âhanded it over to\add* a powerful nationÂŠ347056 to deal withÂŠ347054 it accordingÂŠ347060 to what its wickednessÂŠ347060 deserves. I've thrownÂŠ347061 it out,
\v 12 and foreigners who were the terror of all the nations cut it off and left it to die. Its branchesÂŠ347075 fell onto the mountainsÂŠ347070 and all the valleysÂŠ347073, and lay brokenÂŠ347076 inÂŠ347078 all the land's ravinesÂŠ347079. ThenÂŠ347063 all the nations onÂŠ347078 earth came out from under its shadeÂŠ347082 and went away from it.
\v 13 All the \add âvarious kinds of\add* birds rested on the trunkÂŠ347091 of the fallenÂŠ347091 tree, and every \add kind of\add* animalÂŠ347102 in the countrysideÂŠ347103 came to its branchesÂŠ347099.
\v 14 That happened so that no other trees that grow by the waters will raise up theirÂŠ347129 foliage to the height of the tallest trees, and that no other trees that grow beside the waters will reach up to that height. They've all been assigned to deathÂŠ347139, to the earthÂŠ347142 below, among humanity'sÂŠ347146 childrenÂŠ347145, withÂŠ347110 thoseÂŠ347149 that go down into the pit.
\p
\v 15 The masterÂŠ347156 YahwehÂŠ347156 says this: On the dayÂŠ347158 when the cedar went down to \add âthe place of the dead\add*, I brought mourning to the earth. I coveredÂŠ347162 the deep waters over it, and I held back the oceans. I held back the great waters, and I brought mourning to LebanonÂŠ347174 for it. So all the treesÂŠ347177 in the countrysideÂŠ347178 mourned because of it.
\v 16 I broughtÂŠ347186 shuddering to the nationsÂŠ347185 atÂŠ347186 the soundÂŠ347182 of its downfallÂŠ347183, when I threw it down to \add âthe place of the dead\add*, along withÂŠ347186 thoseÂŠ347191 who went down into the pit. So I comfortedÂŠ347193 all the trees from EdenÂŠ347200 inÂŠ347186 the lowestÂŠ347195 parts of the earth. Those had been the choicestÂŠ347201 and best trees from LebanonÂŠ347204âthe trees that drank the watersÂŠ347208.
\v 17 They also wentÂŠ347214 down withÂŠ347223 \add @the big tree\add* to \add âthe place of the dead\add*, to the ones who'd been killed by the swordÂŠ347220. Those were its strong armâthoseÂŠ347218 nationsÂŠ347225 who'd lived inÂŠ347223 its shadeÂŠ347223.
\p
\v 18 \add Egypt,\add* which of the trees in Eden was your equal in gloryÂŠ347232 and greatnessÂŠ347233? You'll be broughtÂŠ347237 down with Eden'sÂŠ347236 trees to the lowestÂŠ347247 parts of the earthÂŠ347246 amongÂŠ347234 the uncircumcisedÂŠ347249. You'll live there with thoseÂŠ347253 who were killed by the swordÂŠ347255.â
\m That's \add the fate of\add* Far-oh \add (PharaohÂŠ347257)\add* and all his multitudesÂŠ347260. That's the masterÂŠ347263 Yahweh'sÂŠ347264 declaration.â
