\p
\v 13 In additionÂŠ355032, \add âevery morning someone\add*\f + \fr 46:13 \ft Some of the earliest translations (the Septuagint and the Vulgate) have âheâ here, suggesting it must be the leader.\f* \add âmust provide\add* a one yearÂŠ355035 old lambÂŠ355032 withÂŠ355041 noÂŠ355036 defectsÂŠ355036 to be \add âcompletely burntÂŠ355038 up as an\add* offeringÂŠ355038 to YahwehÂŠ355040.
\v 14 \add AlsoÂŠ355061\add* \add âevery morning\add* someone mustÂŠ355047 provide an offeringÂŠ355047 of four litres of flourÂŠ355059 mixed withÂŠ355049 a litre of \add olive\add* oilÂŠ355053, \add andÂŠ355053\add* \add âthat's a permanentÂŠ355063 requirement\add*.
\v 15 They'll prepare the lambÂŠ355070, the grainÂŠ355073 offering, andÂŠ355066 the oilÂŠ355076, \add âevery morning\add*âa permanent \add daily\add* burntÂŠ355079 offering.
\s1 The leader and the country
\rem /s1 The Prince and the Land
\p
\v 16 The masterÂŠ355086 YahwehÂŠ355086 says this: If the leader gives a giftÂŠ355092 to any of his sons, it becomes his inheritanceâthat is, it'll become his sons' propertyÂŠ355099 \add becauseÂŠ355088\add* it's an inheritance.
\v 17 \add âButÂŠ355103\add* if he gives a giftÂŠ355106 from his inheritance to one of his servantsÂŠ355109, then it'll belongÂŠ355122 to that servant untilÂŠ355112 the yearÂŠ355114 of libertyÂŠ355115, andÂŠ355103 then it'll returnÂŠ355116 to the leader. His inheritance mustÂŠ355105 definitely be for his \add own\add* sonsÂŠ355120.\x + \xo 46:17: \xt Lev 25:10.\x*
\v 18 The leader mustn't take the people's inheritance away from them, evicting them from their own propertyâhe mustÂŠ355126 provide for his sons from his own property so that my people won'tÂŠ355124 be \add âforced off their own inherited land\add*.â
\s1 The temple kitchens
